### System information

- **OS version/distro**: Windows 10 Pro x64
- **.NET Version**: .NET Core 3.0
- **ML.NET Version**: 1.5.0-preview

### Issue

**What did you do?**

Trying to create a data view from a list of IDictionary objects. 

- `IEnumerable<Expando>` or ...
- `IEnumerable<HashTable>` or ...
- `IEnumerable<Dictionary<string, object>>`
- `IEnumerable<Dictionary<string, dynamic>>`

In this case, Keys would be used as column names, and Values as a data. 

**What happened?**

When I add column names or implement ValueGetter, I need to specify a type of the column. 
This code from ValueGetter gives an exception - could not cast type String to ReadOnlyMemory<char>

```C#
  return (ValueGetter<TValue>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name]
```

In this code from data view constructor I don't know how to set column type as "dynamic". 

```C#
  public DictionaryView(IEnumerable<HashTable> items)
  {
    Items = items;

    var builder = new DataViewSchema.Builder();

    foreach (var k in items.First().Keys)
    {
      builder.AddColumn(k, TextDataViewType.Instance); // not sure what data type to use here, because HashTable doesn't have type for its Values
    }
    
    Schema = builder.ToSchema();
  }
```

**What did you expect?**

- how to define all columns as `object` or `dynamic` or ... 
- is it possible to implement custom column type for a data view, something like DataKind.MixedEnumerableFloatString or ... 
- define Switch-Case mapping between System.Type and DataView.Kind like in the pseudo-code below?

```C#
public override ValueGetter<TValue> GetGetter<TValue>(DataViewSchema.Column column)
{
  // Ideally, would be good to have some generic delegate that could return some "dynamic" type instead of hardcoded type-casting 
  // If we iterate over data view collection using cursor, we don't need to know the type of the column 

  switch (column.GetType().Name)
  {
    case "Float": return (ValueGetter<float>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name];
    case "Boolean": return (ValueGetter<bool>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name];
    case "String": return (ValueGetter<ReadOnlyMemory<char>>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name];
  }

  if (column is IEnumerable) 
  {
    return (ValueGetter<IEnumerable<float>>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name];
  }

  return (ValueGetter<TValue>)_enumerator.Current[column.Name];
}
```

